      Prophetic Books
        Primary writing: 8th–6th centuries BC
        Exceptions (e.g., Daniel: 2nd century BC)
      New Testament
        Written within 1st century AD
        Earliest: Galatians/1 Thessalonians (~48–50 AD)
        Latest: 2 Peter (~110 AD) or Revelation (~90–95 AD)
    Textual Transmission
      Vast manuscript evidence
        NT: >5,800 Greek, 10,000 Latin, 9,300 others
        Key codices: Vaticanus & Sinaiticus (4th century AD)
      Major textual traditions
        Alexandrian, Western, Byzantine
      Textual variants
        Numerous but mostly minor
        Do not alter core doctrines
        Reconstructed via textual criticism
    Canonical Formation
      Gradual process
        Early consensus by 2nd century AD
        Core NT books widely accepted
      Official ratification in 4th century AD
        Final 27-book NT canon recognized
    Theological Themes
      Covenant
        OT: God's covenant with Israel
        NT: New covenant in Christ
      Redemption
        OT: Sacrifice, prophecy, exile/return
        NT: Fulfillment in Jesus' sacrifice
      God's relationship with humanity
        OT: Law, prophecy, wisdom
        NT: Grace, church, eternal life
    Translation History
      Ancient versions
        Septuagint (Greek OT, 3rd–2nd century BC)
        Vulgate (Latin, 5th century AD)
      Vernacular movement
        Tyndale's English Bible (16th century)
        King James Version (1611)
      Modern translation bases
        Textus Receptus (Byzantine)
          :KJV, NKJV
        Critical Text (Alexandrian)
